The '''Sizewell C nuclear power station''' is a project to construct an addition to the existing nuclear power station at [[Sizewell]], [[Suffolk]], England. It will involve a 3,200{{nbsp}}[[MWe]] [[nuclear power]] station with two [[EPR (nuclear reactor)|EPR]] reactors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sizewell C proposals |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/proposals |access-date=10 July 2020 |archive-date=29 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200629220546/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/proposals |url-status=live}}</ref> The project was proposed by a consortium of [[EDF Energy]] and [[China General Nuclear Power Group]], who at the time owned 80% and 20% of the project respectively.

In 2022, the UK Government announced a buy-out to allow for the exit of CGN from the project and forming a 50% stake with EDF, though EDF expected this to fall below 20% following anticipated external investment. The final investment decision was made on 22 July 2025, with the UK government taking an initial shareholding of 44.9% (specifically the [[Secretary of State for Energy Security and Net Zero]]), with the remainder consisting of [[Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec|La Caisse]], [[Centrica]], EDF, and Amber Infrastructure. The power station is expected to meet up to 7% of the UK's electricity demand, once the addition has been constructed.<ref name="wnn EDF">{{cite news |title=Cost of new Sizewell C nuclear plant put at £20bn |newspaper=Financial Times |date=25 June 2020 |url=https://www.ft.com/content/77c209f7-6d18-4609-ac3c-77d1b5b82b34 |access-date=29 December 2021 |last1=Thomas |first1=Nathalie |last2=Mancini |first2=Donato Paolo |archive-date=29 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229220023/https://www.ft.com/content/77c209f7-6d18-4609-ac3c-77d1b5b82b34 |url-status=live}}</ref>

The project commenced in 2024,<ref>{{cite news |title=Court of Appeal dismisses anti-SZC claims |url=https://www.sizewellc.com/news-views/court-of-appeal-dismisses-anti-szc-claims/ |publisher=Sizewell C |date=2023-12-21 |access-date=2024-01-09 |archive-date=9 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240109144641/https://www.sizewellc.com/news-views/court-of-appeal-dismisses-anti-szc-claims/ |url-status=live}}</ref> with construction taking between nine and twelve years, depending on developments at the [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]], which is also being developed by [[EDF Energy]] and which shares major similarities with the Sizewell plant. The reactors are expected to have a service lifetime of 60 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/articles/sizewell-c-reports-project-progress-to-parliament |title=Sizewell C reports project progress to parliament |work=World Nuclear News |date=31 January 2025 |access-date=9 February 2025}}</ref>

The project has drawn significant criticism and ongoing protest from those who live near the site, as well as environmentalists including [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] spokespeople who note that four acres of woodland will be cut down and the site will further encroach on [[RSPB Minsmere]]: a nature reserve which is immediately adjacent to the new site.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2020-10-08 |title=Sizewell: Nuclear campaigners' bid to save woodland rejected |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-54465228 |access-date=2026-04-19 |work=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Sizewell C Nuclear Power Station |url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/helping-nature/what-we-do/influence-government-and-business/casework/sizewell-c-nuclear-power-station-case-study |access-date=2026-04-19 |website=www.rspb.org.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-01-23 |title=Suffolk MP writes to Sizewell C but refuses to call for a halt to new power station |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/24876996.suffolk-coastal-mp-said-priority-hold-sizewell-account/ |access-date=2026-04-19 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |language=en}}</ref>

==History==
In 2008, the government decided that new nuclear sites should be constructed on existing sites to replace the UK's ageing fleet of reactors.<ref>{{cite news |title=New nuclear plants get go-ahead |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7179579.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=10 January 2008 |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=14 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314020702/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7179579.stm |url-status=live}}</ref> In 2010 the government revealed that the [[Sizewell nuclear power stations|Sizewell power station site]] was one of the eight locations at which it intended to allow the development to occur.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nuclear power: Eight sites identified for future plants |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |publisher=BBC News |date=18 October 2010 |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=19 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019043151/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |url-status=live}}</ref> Following this, [[EDF Energy]] put forward proposals for the Sizewell site in November 2012, where it planned to construct two [[EPR (nuclear reactor)|EPR]] reactors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Initial Proposals and Options Consultation Document Summary |url=https://edf.thirdlight.com/pf.tlx/mi4muzRmu0s1b7 |publisher=EDF Energy |date=November 2012 |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=11 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200711014954/https://edf.thirdlight.com/pf.tlx/mi4muzRmu0s1b7 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2015, as a part of the government's strategy to open the UK up to China, it was reported that after talks with China agreements had been made to develop three nuclear power plants including Sizewell C, [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station|Hinkley Point C]] and [[Bradwell B nuclear power station|Bradwell B]]; however, agreements had not yet been made over financing the Sizewell project, with the final agreement likely to be made after the construction of Hinkley Point C had started.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hinkley Point nuclear agreement reached |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34587650 |publisher=BBC News |date=21 October 2015 |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=21 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021052531/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34587650 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 21 October 2015, EDF Energy announced that it had 'agreed the Heads of Terms of a wider UK partnership for the joint development of new nuclear power stations at Sizewell in Suffolk and Bradwell in Essex' with [[China General Nuclear Power Group]] (CGN). At the same time, EDF Energy also announced that it 'will take an 80% share and CGN will take a 20% share' during the development phase of the project.<ref name="edfenergy.com hinkley">{{cite press release |title=Agreements in place for construction of Hinkley Point C nuclear power station |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/hinkley-point-c/news-views/agreements-in-place |publisher=EDF Energy |date=2015-10-21 |access-date=2020-10-21 |archive-date=11 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200711024546/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/hinkley-point-c/news-views/agreements-in-place |url-status=live}}</ref>

Following extensive consultation with the local community, on 27 May 2020 EDF Energy announced that it had submitted a development consent order application.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 May 2020 |title=Sizewell C submits planning application |url=https://namrc.co.uk/industry/sizewell-c-planning-application/ |website=Nuclear AMRC |language=en-GB |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=11 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200711214736/https://namrc.co.uk/industry/sizewell-c-planning-application/ |url-status=live}}</ref> EDF stated that 25,000 job opportunities would be created and targeted 70% of the investment to be spent in UK. The plant would largely replicate the Hinkley Point C design to reuse experience and attempt to lower costs.<ref name="edfenergy-20200602">{{Cite press release |date=27 May 2020 |title=Sizewell C submits planning application |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/media-centre/news-releases/sizewell-c-dco |publisher=EDF Energy |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=27 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200727211654/https://www.edfenergy.com/media-centre/news-releases/sizewell-c-dco |url-status=live}}</ref>

In June 2020, EDF had yet to organise financing, and could not take on more construction risk in the UK. EDF was looking to the UK government to assist with financing either by offering a Regulated Asset Base (RAB) model used on less risky infrastructure, though that puts an immediate cost burden on end consumers, or with other approaches such as a government equity stake in the development.<ref name="ft-20200602">{{Cite news |last1=Nathalie Thomas |last2=Jim Pickard |date=2 June 2020 |title=Plan for new UK nuclear plant under intense scrutiny |work=Financial Times |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e3221ef-ac1e-43cc-8d68-e1397ca0637f |url-access=subscription |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=18 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200618071309/https://www.ft.com/content/4e3221ef-ac1e-43cc-8d68-e1397ca0637f |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 30 June 2020, EDF Energy announced that it had applied to the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]] (ONR) for a licence to build and operate Sizewell C. The ONR is responsible for the safe operation of nuclear sites in the UK and for permitting new nuclear site licences{{snd}}one of the key regulatory requirements for building and operating a new power station.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sizewell C applies for a licence to build and operate in Suffolk |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/news-views/sizewell-c-applies-licence-build-and-operate-in-suffolk |date=30 June 2020 |access-date=8 July 2020 |archive-date=8 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200708081052/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/news-views/sizewell-c-applies-licence-build-and-operate-in-suffolk |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 11 September 2020, Suffolk county council said that it could not support the plans for the construction of Sizewell C in its current form,<ref>{{cite web |title=County Council unable to support plans for Sizewell C |url=https://www.suffolk.gov.uk/council-and-democracy/council-news/show/county-council-unable-to-support-plans-for-sizewell-c |website=Suffolk County Council |access-date=16 October 2020 |date=11 September 2020 |archive-date=19 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919085033/https://www.suffolk.gov.uk/council-and-democracy/council-news/show/county-council-unable-to-support-plans-for-sizewell-c |url-status=live}}</ref> with the council saying on 23 October 2020 that the plans "do not go far enough" to mitigate the impact on the local community and on the local environment. The council said that a lack of support for the project was not the issue, and that it is that EDF "simply does not appropriately and sensitively address the impacts on our communities and the environment".<ref>{{cite news |title=Sizewell C nuclear power station plans 'do not address local impact' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-54247404 |access-date=16 October 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=23 September 2020 |archive-date=11 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201011152654/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-54247404 |url-status=live}}</ref> EDF responded by submitting significant changes to the project which aimed to significantly reduce the number of Heavy Goods Vehicles delivering the materials required for the project by having them delivered by train and sea instead. The plans also proposed to increase the amount of land for the creation of fen meadow to help increase the net gain of biodiversity following the completion of the project. A consultation period began on 16 November 2020, which lasted for 30 days and which will inform all of the stakeholders in the project about the proposals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Changes submitted for Sizewell C project to cut HGV construction traffic |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/edf-sizewell-c-plans-14-changes-1-6886011 |access-date=16 October 2020 |publisher=East Anglian Daily Times |date=16 October 2020 |archive-date=17 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201017214445/https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/edf-sizewell-c-plans-14-changes-1-6886011 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 31 October 2020, the BBC claimed that the government was 'close' to giving the project the green light following intensified talks with EDF, with government officials insisting that it "remains committed to new nuclear" following the withdrawal of [[Horizon Nuclear Power|Horizon]] from Wylfa and Oldbury. The BBC also reported that the government had increased its interest in taking a stake in the project following work on the second reactor at Hinkley Point C being completed 30% faster than the first reactor, which 'is thought to have substantially mitigated' the risk in taking a stake in the project.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Simon Jack |title=New nuclear plant at Sizewell set for green light |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-54754016 |access-date=1 November 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=31 October 2020 |archive-date=31 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201031234502/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-54754016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Will Jefford |title=Government 'close' to giving Sizewell C green light, reports say |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/business/sizewell-c-green-ligth-reports-1-6909641 |access-date=1 November 2020 |publisher=East Anglian Daily Times |date=31 October 2020 |archive-date=1 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201101013755/https://www.eadt.co.uk/business/sizewell-c-green-ligth-reports-1-6909641 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 14 December 2020, the UK government published an energy white paper setting out its plans to "transition to [[Carbon neutrality|net zero]]",<ref>{{cite web |title=ENERGY WHITE PAPER Powering our Net Zero Future |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-white-paper-powering-our-net-zero-future |website=Gov.uk |publisher=UK Government |access-date=19 December 2020 |date=14 December 2020 |archive-date=18 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201218204343/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-white-paper-powering-our-net-zero-future |url-status=live}}</ref> and announced the start of negotiations with EDF, with a view to starting investment on "at least one" new power station before the end of the current parliament in 2024.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK to start talks with EDF on funding for Sizewell C : New Nuclear - World Nuclear News |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/UK-to-start-talks-with-EDF-on-funding-for-Sizewell |work=www.world-nuclear-news.org}}</ref> CGN is thought to be planning to withdraw from the project.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sizewell C: Government in talks to fund £20bn nuclear plant |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-55299511 |work=BBC News |date=14 December 2020 |access-date=14 December 2020 |archive-date=14 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214155956/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-55299511 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 20 July 2022, the planning application was approved and a Development Consent Order was issued by the Secretary of State.<ref name="dco2022">{{cite web |title=The Sizewell C Project development consent decision announced |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-sizewell-c-project-development-consent-decision-announced |publisher=UK Government |date=20 July 2022 |access-date=20 July 2022 |archive-date=20 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220720110339/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-sizewell-c-project-development-consent-decision-announced |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 3 November 2022, the plant was placed under review in the government's effort to cut spending.<ref name=bbc-20221104>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-63507630 |title=Sizewell C new nuclear plant under review |last=Jack |first=Simon |work=BBC News |date=4 November 2022 |access-date=4 November 2022 |archive-date=4 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221104002311/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-63507630 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] Jeremy Hunt confirmed on 17 November 2022 that construction would go ahead, with initial contracts to be signed "within weeks".<ref>{{cite news |title=Sizewell C nuclear plant to go ahead, chancellor confirms |url=https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2022-11-17/sizewell-c-nuclear-plant-to-go-ahead-chancellor-confirms |work=ITV News |date=17 November 2022 |language=en}}</ref> Security concerns about China caused the government to buy CGN out of the development for just over £100{{nbsp}}million in late 2022, leaving it co-owned by EDF and the UK government.<ref name=ft-20221129>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a9a34ea3-649f-4a47-a4c8-ee269e07eccc |title=UK government to pay Chinese group £100mn to exit Sizewell C |last=Pickard |first=Jim |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=29 November 2022 |access-date=12 September 2023 |archive-date=23 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231023211608/https://www.ft.com/content/a9a34ea3-649f-4a47-a4c8-ee269e07eccc |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 15 January 2024, construction of Sizewell C formally began; Aldeburgh & Leiston Councillor Tom Daly stated that "Sizewell C Ltd confirmed that the construction of Sizewell C new nuclear power station commenced on Monday".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Daly |first=Tom |date=16 January 2024 |title=Statement following commencement of construction for Sizewell C |url=https://www.eastsuffolk.gov.uk/news/statement-following-commencement-of-construction-for-sizewell-c/}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Chambers |first=Sarah |date=15 January 2024 |title=Sizewell C era begins as construction work gets green light |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/24050141.sizewell-c-era-begins-construction-work-gets-green-light/}}</ref>

