|-
|Amber Infrastructure Group || 0.25 || 3%
|-
|[[Nuclear Liabilities Fund]],<br/>co-owned by EDF and UK government, managed by Amber || {{ndash}} || 7.6% (option for 10%)
|}

{{As of|2025|7}}, the Sizewell C project is expected to cost £38{{nbsp}}billion.<ref name=38billion/> It was originally expected to cost £20{{nbsp}}billion to £30{{nbsp}}billion.<ref name=":1"/><ref name=":0" /><ref name="bloomberg-approve">{{cite news |title=Boris Johnson Approves Funding for Sizewell C Nuclear Plant |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-21/boris-johnson-approves-funding-for-sizewell-c-nuclear-plant |access-date=28 September 2022 |work=Bloomberg UK |agency=The Press Association |date=21 August 2022 |archive-date=21 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220821100528/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-21/boris-johnson-approves-funding-for-sizewell-c-nuclear-plant |url-status=live}}</ref> The project was initially led by EDF Energy and CGN, which in 2020 owned 80% and 20% of the project, respectively.<ref name="edfenergy.com hinkley" />

EDF sought UK government assistance with financing either by offering a [[Nuclear power in the United Kingdom#Regulated Asset Base financing model|Regulated Asset Base model]], though that puts an immediate cost burden on end consumers, or with other approaches such as a government equity stake in the development, as the company is unwilling to take on further risk within the UK.<ref name=ft-20200602 /> On 30 June 2020, EDF announced that it had applied to the Office for Nuclear Regulation for a licence to build and operate Sizewell C.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sizewell C applies for a licence to build and operate in Suffolk |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/news-views/sizewell-c-applies-licence-build-and-operate-in-suffolk |access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-date=8 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200708081052/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/sizewell-c/news-views/sizewell-c-applies-licence-build-and-operate-in-suffolk |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 14 July 2020, 32 companies and organisations from the UK nuclear supply chain formed a consortium to encourage the government to support the state-guaranteed financing model for Sizewell C,<ref>{{cite web |title=New industrial consortium backs Sizewell C |url=https://www.sizewellcsupplychain.co.uk/news/new-industrial-consortium-backs-sizewell-c/ |website=Sizewell C supply chain |date=14 July 2020 |publisher=EDF |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=9 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809234102/https://www.sizewellcsupplychain.co.uk/news/new-industrial-consortium-backs-sizewell-c/ |url-status=live}}</ref> Regulated Asset Base, which the consortium says would reduce the cost of new nuclear projects by having consumers pay the cost upfront through their energy bills.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sizewell C Consortium urges decision on funding |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Sizewell-C-Consortium-urges-decision-on-funding |website=World Nuclear News |date=14 July 2020 |access-date=15 July 2020 |archive-date=15 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200715032151/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Sizewell-C-Consortium-urges-decision-on-funding |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 30 September 2020, Jean-Bernard Lévy, EDF's chairman and CEO, demanded that the Treasury provided clarity on the future of nuclear funding following [[Hitachi]]'s withdrawal from the [[Wylfa Newydd nuclear power station]] project which was set to cost £20{{nbsp}}billion, citing a lack of viable funding.<ref>{{cite web |title=UK / Head Of EDF 'Demands Clarity' on Funding For New Nuclear Projects include Sizewell C |url=https://neutronbytes.com/ |website=Neutron Bytes |access-date=10 October 2020 |date=3 October 2020 |archive-date=4 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201004181054/https://neutronbytes.com/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=David Dalton |title=UK / Head Of EDF To 'Demand Clarity' On Funding For New Nuclear |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/head-of-edf-to-demand-clarity-on-funding-for-new-nuclear-9-3-2020 |access-date=10 October 2020 |publisher=NucNet |date=30 September 2020 |archive-date=11 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201011070903/https://www.nucnet.org/news/head-of-edf-to-demand-clarity-on-funding-for-new-nuclear-9-3-2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 14 December 2020, following the release of the UK government's long-awaited energy white paper, the government announced that it had started consultations with EDF to take a stake in the project following concerns that CGN is backing out of the project, which would leave a financing gap. The government also warned that any stake in the project would be 'subject to approval on areas such as value for money and affordability' with the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]], [[Alok Sharma]], saying, "We are starting negotiations with EDF, it is not a green light on the construction".<ref>{{cite news |author1=Roger Harrabin & Simon Read |title=Sizewell C: Government in talks to fund £20bn nuclear plant |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-55299511 |access-date=19 December 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=14 December 2020 |archive-date=18 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201218182930/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-55299511 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In January 2022, the UK government invested £100{{nbsp}}million towards continued development of the project.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dalton |first1=David |title=UK / Government Invests £100m In EDF's £20bn Sizewell C Nuclear Power Station |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/government-invests-gbp100m-in-edf-s-gbp20bn-sizewell-c-nuclear-power-station-1-4-2022 |work=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency |date=27 January 2022 |access-date=7 April 2022 |archive-date=29 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220429070844/https://www.nucnet.org/news/government-invests-gbp100m-in-edf-s-gbp20bn-sizewell-c-nuclear-power-station-1-4-2022 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2022, it was announced that the UK government and EDF would each take a 20% stake in the project, with infrastructure investors and pension funds expected to take up the remaining 60%.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sizewell C nuclear power station: Government to take 20% stake |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-60889001 |work=BBC News |date=27 March 2022 |access-date=7 April 2022 |archive-date=7 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220407091630/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-60889001 |url-status=live}}</ref> Funding was also agreed to improve local activities, courtesy of the Sizewell C and the [[East Anglia Array]] projects.<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy Projects Update |url=https://www.thesuffolkcoast.co.uk/shares/Updates-on-Energy-Projects---Paul-Wood-East-Suffolk-Council.pdf |publisher=[[East Suffolk District]] |access-date=22 July 2023 |archive-date=8 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230308062604/https://www.thesuffolkcoast.co.uk/shares/Updates-on-Energy-Projects---Paul-Wood-East-Suffolk-Council.pdf |url-status=live}}</ref>

In August 2022, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported expected costs were £20{{nbsp}}billion to be paid with £1.7{{nbsp}}billion of taxpayer money and a surcharge on customer energy bills through the Regulated Asset Base model. [[Barclays]] had been hired to find new financial backing.<ref name=guardian-20220808/>

In November 2022, the UK government announced that it was taking over a 50% stake in the project for £679{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=wnn-20221129>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/UK-government-takes-50-stake,-gives-go-ahead-for-S |title=UK government takes 50% stake, confirms backing for Sizewell C |website=World Nuclear News |date=29 November 2022 |access-date=4 February 2023 |archive-date=1 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230201062434/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/UK-government-takes-50-stake,-gives-go-ahead-for-S |url-status=live}}</ref>
In February 2023, EDF confirmed that following anticipated external investment its shareholding in the project will be no more than 19.9%. Project costs estimates vary from £20{{nbsp}}billion to £35{{nbsp}}billion.<ref name=cityam-20230218>{{cite news |url=https://www.cityam.com/edf-inflation-drives-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-plant-costs-from-26bn-to-33bn/ |title=EDF: Inflation drives Hinkley Point C nuclear plant costs from £26bn to £33bn |last=Earl |first=Nicholas |newspaper=City A.M. |date=18 February 2023 |access-date=20 February 2023 |archive-date=20 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230220122247/https://www.cityam.com/edf-inflation-drives-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-plant-costs-from-26bn-to-33bn/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2023, the UK government issued a pre-qualification questionnaire to prospective investors; successful applicants will be invited to participate in the bidding process. The government have made an additional £511{{nbsp}}million available for project development and site preparation ahead of the bidding process.<ref name=wnn-20230918>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Private-investment-sought-for-Sizewell-C-project |title=Private investment sought for Sizewell C project |website=World Nuclear News |date=18 September 2023 |access-date=18 September 2023 |archive-date=19 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230919102327/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Private-investment-sought-for-Sizewell-C-project |url-status=live}}</ref>

In January 2024, the UK government announced £1.3{{nbsp}}billion of additional funding for the project for infrastructure work such as roads and rail lines, allowing construction work to progress prior to the final investment decision being made.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2024-01-23 |title=Sizewell opponents apply to Supreme Court as government commits £1bn |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-68056919 |access-date=2024-01-23 |work=BBC News |language=en-GB |archive-date=23 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240123163840/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-suffolk-68056919 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20240123>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/UK-invests-further-GBP1-3bn-to-keep-Sizewell-C-on |title=UK invests further GBP1.3bn to keep Sizewell C on schedule |website=World Nuclear News |date=23 January 2024 |access-date=25 January 2024 |archive-date=25 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125134209/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/UK-invests-further-GBP1-3bn-to-keep-Sizewell-C-on |url-status=live}}</ref>

In August 2024, the UK government announced up to £5.5{{nbsp}}billion of additional funding through the Sizewell C Development Expenditure (Devex) Subsidy Scheme "to enable continued support to the development of the proposed new nuclear power plant Sizewell C (SZC) to the point of a Final Investment Decision (FID)", "provided subject to relevant approvals, including the upcoming Spending Review".<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 August 2024 |title=Sizewell C Development Expenditure (Devex) Subsidy Scheme |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sizewell-c-development-expenditure-subsidy-scheme/sizewell-c-development-expenditure-devex-subsidy-scheme}}</ref> In the subsequent Autumn Budget, the UK government provided "£2.7{{nbsp}}billion of funding to continue Sizewell C's development through 2025-26",<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 October 2024 |title=Autumn Budget 2024 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/autumn-budget-2024/autumn-budget-2024-html}}</ref> however "[[HM Treasury]] has clarified that the £2.7bn is not new funding but rather a sum that would be invested either via the previously announced £5.5bn Devex scheme, or through a separate FID subsidy scheme that would be established at the point of FID."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pashby |first=Tom |date=30 October 2024 |title=Autumn Budget: Government commits additional £2.7bn to Sizewell C |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/autumn-budget-government-commits-additional-2-7bn-to-sizewell-c-30-10-2024/}}</ref>

In December 2024, Sizewell C's joint managing director Nigel Cann stated "We have five investors in the process and potentially more" and are aiming to take the final investment decision in 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Twidale |first=Susanna |date=5 December 2024 |title=Five investors in UK Sizewell C nuclear stake bidding process, developer says |website=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/five-investors-uk-sizewell-c-nuclear-stake-bidding-process-developer-says-2024-12-05/}}</ref>

In January 2025, it was reported that "one senior government figure and two well-placed industry sources" said the cost of the project was "likely to reach close to £40bn".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=Millard |first2=Rachel |last3=Plimmer |first3=Gill |date=13 January 2024 |title=Cost of Sizewell C nuclear project expected to rise close to £40bn |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0b483728-de5b-4f2e-8d00-c49885c572c9}}</ref> In response, EDF said the £40{{nbsp}}billion figure was "not accurate", and it was reported that "the government also said it did not recognise this sum".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Jack |first1=Simon |last2=Cunningham |first2=Alice |date=15 January 2025 |title=EDF reject claims Sizewell C will cost £40bn |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cvglnnqq08yo}}</ref> That month, the French state auditor advised EDF not to proceed with Sizewell C until it had reduced its exposure on Hinkley Point C.<ref name=ft-20250221>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c546117d-1fbc-47c8-93a8-dd823311d2ac |title=UK's Hinkley Point C nuclear plant yet to attract new investors, says EDF boss |last1=Johnston |first1=Ian |last2=Millard |first2=Rachel |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=21 February 2025 |access-date=21 February 2025}}</ref> That month, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' stated that the UK government had already committed £8{{nbsp}}billion to the project.<ref name=st-20250119>{{cite news |url=https://www.thetimes.com/business-money/companies/article/whats-happening-with-britains-nuclear-plants-and-when-will-they-be-built-tr6v0986f |title=Over time, over budget... will our new nuclear plants ever be built? |last=Yeomans |first=Jon |newspaper=The Sunday Times |location=London |url-access=subscription |date=19 January 2025 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20250119003327/https://www.thetimes.com/business-money/companies/article/whats-happening-with-britains-nuclear-plants-and-when-will-they-be-built-tr6v0986f |archive-date=19 January 2025}}</ref>

On 10 June 2025, the government announced that Sizewell C had been allocated government capital investment of £14.2{{nbsp}}billion during the [[Spending Review#2025 Spending Review|2025 spending review]] period (2026 to 2030). The Treasury expects 10,000 jobs to be created and enough power generated to provide electricity for six{{nbsp}}million homes.<ref name="BBCc4gr3nd5zy6o">{{cite news |last1=Cunningham |first1=Alice |title=Sizewell C nuclear plant gets £14bn go-ahead from government |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c4gr3nd5zy6o |access-date=10 June 2025 |work=BBC News |date=10 June 2025}}</ref> The project is still awaiting the Final Investment Decision, when the financial deal with incoming private investors for the remaining capital investment is made, and the cost of the project is disclosed.<ref name=wato-20250610>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m002dbsy |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250612154057/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m002dbsy |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 June 2025 |title=Government confirms huge nuclear investment |last=Pyke |first=Julia |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |work=World at One |time=12m28s |quote=''Julia Pyke (Joint Managing Director, Sizewell C Limited):'' We are going to talk about the cost of the project at the final investment decision which is the date when the deal with the incoming private investors is done. |date=10 June 2025 |access-date=12 June 2025}}</ref><ref name=bbc-20250609>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/c3v50qy35pwt |title=No blank cheque for Sizewell C says Starmer, as £14.2bn investment confirmed |last=Goldsmith |first=Adam |work=BBC News |date=9 June 2025 |access-date=12 June 2025}}</ref> The Final Investment Decision should take place in summer 2025.<ref name=hansard-20250610>{{cite web |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2025-06-10/debates/1F2B231C-71EF-4F1B-A9D4-268ABF38B5C1/NuclearPowerInvestment |title=Nuclear Power: Investment |last=Miliband |first=Ed |publisher=UK Parliament |work=Hansard |id=Volume 768, Column 814 |quote=we are currently doing the private sector capital raise. When that is complete, we will proceed to the final investment decision, which will take place this summer. |date=10 June 2025 |access-date=13 June 2025}}</ref>

On 22 July 2025, the government signed the final investment decision.<ref name=38billion>{{Cite web |date=22 July 2025|title=Sizewell C nuclear power plant costs rise to £38bn |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cev03wer0p2o |first1 = Mariam |last1 = Issimdar |first2= Rachel |last2 = Clun|access-date=22 July 2025 |work=BBC News }}</ref>  The UK government confirmed it would be taking an initial stake of 44.9% in the project, with the remainder consisting of [[Caisse de dépôt et placement du Québec|La Caisse]] (20%), [[Centrica]] (15%), EDF (12.5%), and Amber Infrastructure (7.6%). There is also a proposed £5 billion debt guarantee from [[Bpifrance]] Assurance Export, to back commercial bank loans. The [[National Wealth Fund (United Kingdom)|National Wealth Fund]] is to support the majority of the project's debt finance, alongside Bpifrance.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |date=22 July 2025 |title=Sizewell C gets green light with final investment decision |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/sizewell-c-gets-green-light-with-final-investment-decision |access-date=22 July 2025 |website=GOV.UK |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ambrose |first=Jillian |date=2025-07-22 |title=UK strikes deal with private investors to build £38bn Sizewell C nuclear power plant |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2025/jul/22/uk-deal-sizewell-c-nuclear-power-plant-investors-edf |access-date=2025-07-22 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> 

The equity and debt finance raised will exceed the construction cost to manage potential overruns. The government claims suppliers are incentivised to reduce costs and investors would lose potential revenue in case of overruns, reducing risk for taxpayers. The government is using a Regulated Asset Base funding model, introduced in the Nuclear Energy (Financing) Act 2022.  With an estimated construction cost of £38 billion (representing a 20% saving over Hinkley Point C), this model means that monthly consumer bills increase by £1 already in the ten years of construction time, when no electricity is yet generated. The power station is projected to save the electricity system £2 billion a year, once operational.<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Morby |first=Aaron |date=22 July 2025 |title=Sizewell C go-ahead as funding deal signed at £38bn |url=https://www.constructionenquirer.com/2025/07/22/sizewell-c-go-ahead-as-funding-deal-signed-at-38bn/ |access-date=22 July 2025 |website=Construction Enquirer |language=en-GB}}</ref> In November 2025, the financing deal was agreed.<ref name=nei-20251106>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/sizewell-c-achieves-financial-close/? |title=Sizewell C achieves financial close |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=6 November 2025 |access-date=9 November 2025}}</ref>

==Criticism and opposition==

===Opposition groups===
[[File:Sizewell C protest sign.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|A Stop Sizewell C protest sign, on a Suffolk roadside]]
Groups that opposed the construction of the plant include Together Against Sizewell C (TASC) and Stop Sizewell C.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.suffolknews.co.uk/ipswich/news/absoulutely-right-protestors-welcome-sizewell-c-plans-rev-9282594/ |title=Suffolk protest groups Stop Sizewell C and Together Against Sizewell C welcome nuclear plant review plans |first1=Ash |last1=Jones |date=4 November 2022 |access-date=22 December 2022 |archive-date=22 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221222064756/https://www.suffolknews.co.uk/ipswich/news/absoulutely-right-protestors-welcome-sizewell-c-plans-rev-9282594/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

TASC sought a judicial review of the East Suffolk Council's decision to grant planning permission in September 2019 for preparatory works on the site, which would involve the felling of 229 trees as well as the demolition of buildings on the Sizewell B site. The group claimed that the decision was unlawful and that proper investigations into the potential scale of environmental damage had not occurred.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sizewell: Nuclear campaigners' bid to save woodland rejected |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-54465228 |access-date=9 October 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=8 October 2020 |archive-date=15 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201015123940/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-suffolk-54465228 |url-status=live}}</ref> The bid to block the works was brought to the High Court on behalf of TASC by a local resident and former Labour Suffolk county councillor, Joan Girling.{{importance inline|reason=Is the name and former role of the person who brought the claim to court of any significance to this article?|date=February 2024}} The court heard the case on 8 September 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=High Court Refuses TASC Coronation Wood appeal but TASC resolved to continue battle against Sizewell C development |url=https://tasizewellc.org.uk/high-court-refuses-tasc-coronation-wood-appeal-but-tasc-resolved-to-continue-battle-against-sizewell-c-development/ |website=Together Against Sizewell C |access-date=10 October 2020 |date=1 October 2020 |archive-date=22 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022083850/https://tasizewellc.org.uk/high-court-refuses-tasc-coronation-wood-appeal-but-tasc-resolved-to-continue-battle-against-sizewell-c-development/ |url-status=live}}</ref> and ruled that the [[Habitat destruction|habitat loss]] would be "minor" and "not significant". Mr Justice Holgate rejected the attempt to block the works, and said that he "did not accept East Suffolk Council acted irrationally".

An EDF spokesperson responded to the rulings by saying that "The judge acknowledged the robust nature of the report provided by East Suffolk Council regarding the environmental impact of the work. The report, which was informed by the council [[Arboriculture|arboriculturist]], found that the majority (73%) of the 229 trees that need to be removed from Coronation Wood are low quality plantation wood with a limited life expectancy and limited amenity value. It was judged that this loss would be 'balanced' by the planting of over 2,500 juvenile woodland trees, including a mixture of broadleaf and coniferous species appropriate for the prevailing soil and coastal conditions."<ref>{{cite magazine |author1=Nadine Buddoo |title=Sizewell C spurred by High Court ruling on planning permission |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/sizewell-c-spurred-by-high-court-ruling-on-planning-permission-07-10-2020/ |magazine=New Civil Engineer |publisher=New Civil Engineer |access-date=10 October 2020 |date=7 October 2020 |archive-date=9 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009195855/https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/sizewell-c-spurred-by-high-court-ruling-on-planning-permission-07-10-2020/ |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 6 October 2020, TASC and the Stop Sizewell C group delivered a petition with over 10,400 signatures to Downing Street,<ref>{{cite web |title=STOP SIZEWELL C |url=https://www.stopsizewellcpetition.com/ |website=Stop Sizewell C Petition |access-date=10 October 2020 |archive-date=3 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201003095558/https://www.stopsizewellcpetition.com/ |url-status=live}}</ref> the Treasury and the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, calling for the government to stop Sizewell C as the plans would be costly, risky and would not positively contribute to net zero until 2040.<ref>{{cite web |title=TASC & SSC deliver petition to No 10 with over 10,000 signatures 06/10/20 |url=https://tasizewellc.org.uk/tasc-ssc-deliver-petition-to-no-10-with-over-10000-signatures/ |website=Together Against Sizewell C |date=6 October 2020 |access-date=10 October 2020 |archive-date=22 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201022083458/https://tasizewellc.org.uk/tasc-ssc-deliver-petition-to-no-10-with-over-10000-signatures/ |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Katy Sandalls |title=Anti-Sizewell C campaigners deliver 10,000 signature petition to Downing St opposing n-power station |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/sizewell-c-campaigners-deliver-petition-to-downing-street-1-6872025 |access-date=10 October 2020 |publisher=East Anglian Daily Times |date=6 October 2020 |archive-date=9 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009164752/https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/sizewell-c-campaigners-deliver-petition-to-downing-street-1-6872025 |url-status=live}}</ref>

Stop Sizewell C is the campaign name of Theberton and Eastbridge Action Group on Sizewell (TEAGS). TEAGS was formed in 2013 by representatives of the Suffolk parish of Theberton and Eastbridge, which neighbours the proposed Sizewell C construction site, in order to give a voice to the community. TEAGS did not initially oppose Sizewell C, but after eight years of engagement with EDF and other stakeholders, the group changed its name to Stop Sizewell C.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=26 February 2014 |title=Stop Sizewell C - About Us |url=https://stopsizewellc.org/join/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201113005649/https://stopsizewellc.org/join/ |archive-date=13 November 2020 |access-date=2020-11-11 |website=Stop Sizewell C |language=en-GB |url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2023, the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]] ruled that the Government's decision to approve the site was lawful, following a challenge from TASC which argued that the site would cause 'irreparable damage' to the Suffolk coast.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sizewell C nuclear power plant approval ruled lawful by Court of Appeal |url=https://news.sky.com/story/sizewell-c-nuclear-power-plant-approval-ruled-lawful-by-court-of-appeal-13034799 |access-date=2023-12-20 |website=Sky News |language=en |archive-date=20 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231220124514/https://news.sky.com/story/sizewell-c-nuclear-power-plant-approval-ruled-lawful-by-court-of-appeal-13034799 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In May 2024, after an appeal by TASC, the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] refused to review the Court of Appeal decision as "the application does not raise an arguable point of law".<ref name="TCI-14May2024">{{cite news |title=Supreme Court backs Sizewell planning permission |url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/supreme-court-backs-sizewell-planning-permission |access-date=14 May 2024 |work=The Construction Index |date=14 May 2024}}</ref>
In December 2024 the High Court ruled that the challenge filed by TEAGS/Stop Sizewell C had "no chance of success" and was "totally without merit".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Parker |first=Ben |date=3 December 2024 |title=Campaigners lose bid to block Sizewell C |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c0ew14e783qo |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

===Concerns regarding Chinese involvement===
Concerns have been expressed regarding one of the shareholders in the consortium,<ref>{{cite web |title=Spy warning on Chinese nuclear company |url=https://www.thetimes.com/article/spy-warning-on-chinese-nuclear-company-cgn-china-general-nuclear-trrh0hftv |work=The Times |date=24 October 2018 |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=25 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525104125/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/spy-warning-on-chinese-nuclear-company-cgn-china-general-nuclear-trrh0hftv |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Britain's nuclear industry is falling inexorably into Chinese hands |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/01/24/britains-nuclear-industry-falling-inexorably-chinese-hands/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=24 January 2019 |access-date=23 July 2020 |last1=Pagnamenta |first1=Robin |archive-date=10 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200710035345/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/01/24/britains-nuclear-industry-falling-inexorably-chinese-hands/ |url-status=live}}</ref> [[China General Nuclear Power Group]] (known as CGN), which is owned by the Chinese government and has been blacklisted by the [[United States Department of Commerce]] for attempting to acquire advanced U.S. nuclear technology and material for diversion to military use.<ref>{{cite web |title=China General Nuclear Power accused of espionage with its adviser in the US |date=11 August 2016 |url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2002539/china-general-nuclear-power-accused-espionage-its-adviser-us |publisher=South China Morning Post |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=10 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200710032349/https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2002539/china-general-nuclear-power-accused-espionage-its-adviser-us |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Four China Nuclear Industry Companies Added to "Entity List" |url=https://www.pillsburylaw.com/en/news-and-insights/china-industry-entity-list.html |publisher=Pillsbury Winthrop Shaw Pittman LLP |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-date=9 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609075109/https://www.pillsburylaw.com/en/news-and-insights/china-industry-entity-list.html |url-status=live}}</ref>
In September 2020, following Hitachi's decision to withdraw from the [[Wylfa Newydd nuclear power station|Wylfa]] and [[Oldbury Nuclear Power Station#Oldbury B|Oldbury]] projects, the BBC reported that the UK government was looking to replace CGN as an investor and might take a stake in Sizewell C.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jack |first1=Simon |title=Government could take stake in new nuclear station |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-54181748 |work=BBC News |date=16 September 2020 |access-date=17 September 2020 |archive-date=17 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200917092532/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-54181748 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2022, UK Government announced a buy-out to allow for the exit of CGN from the project.<ref name="wnn-20221129" />

===Concerns regarding water consumption===
Some environmental campaigners and Sizewell critics have questioned if it will be possible to meet the plant's need for [[potable water]] without adversely impacting the supplies available to surrounding areas.<ref name="beccles8mar">{{cite news |title=Sizewell C 'threat to water supplies' |url=https://www.becclesandbungayjournal.co.uk/news/sizewell-c-threat-to-water-supplies-1871084 |access-date=27 July 2022 |work=Beccles and Bungay Journal |publisher=Archant Community Media Ltd |date=8 March 2010 |archive-date=27 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727143728/https://www.becclesandbungayjournal.co.uk/news/sizewell-c-threat-to-water-supplies-1871084 |url-status=live}}</ref> Figures released in early 2010 by the Sizewell A and B operators—[[Magnox Ltd]] and EDF, respectively—indicated that the two existing plants were consuming approximately {{convert|920|m3|impgal}} of mains water each day, in addition to the {{convert|5000000|m3|cuft}} of seawater that the operators are permitted to use for cooling systems that do not require treated water.<ref name="beccles8mar" /> Critics estimated that Sizewell C would require a further {{convert|1600|m3|impgal}} of potable water daily, and suggested that EDF were planning to use the mains supply because it would be cheaper than the alternative of establishing a [[desalination]] plant. [[Essex and Suffolk Water]], the mains-water supplier for the area, stated in response that they were satisfied that the water supply would be "sustainable" for the next 25 years even if Sizewell C were to be built.<ref name="beccles8mar" />

However, Essex and Suffolk Water later reversed its position, leading EDF to plan instead on using a temporary desalination plant to provide for construction water needs while also building a permanent {{convert|18|mi|km|order=flip|adj=mid|-long}} pipeline from the [[River Waveney]] to the Sizewell C site{{snd}}but this plan was also halted when in August 2021 Essex and Suffolk Water informed EDF that the [[Environment Agency]] would be curtailing their licences to abstract water from the River Waveney by up to 60%.<ref name="guardian27jul">{{cite news |last1=Atkins |first1=William |title=A new nuclear power station needs a vast supply of water. But where will Sizewell C get it from? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/jul/27/nuclear-power-station-sizewell-c-water-suffolk |access-date=27 July 2022 |work=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd |date=27 July 2022 |archive-date=27 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727142639/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2022/jul/27/nuclear-power-station-sizewell-c-water-suffolk |url-status=live}}</ref> The water company subsequently confirmed that "existing water resources (including the River Waveney) will not be sufficient to meet forecast mains water demand, including the operational demand of Sizewell C," leading EDF to declare that it would rely on a permanent desalination system supplying the plant's needs if no other solution could be found.<ref name="guardian27jul" /> This was accepted by the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]], [[Kwasi Kwarteng]], who held that "the uncertainty over the permanent water supply strategy is not a barrier to granting consent" to the Sizewell C project.<ref name="szc-decision">{{cite letter |first=Fiona |last=Mettam |recipient=Carly Vince (NNB Generation Company (SZC) Limited) |subject=PLANNING ACT 2008: APPLICATION FOR DEVELOPMENT CONSENT FOR THE SIZEWELL C NUCLEAR POWER STATION |date=20 July 2022 |url=https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/wp-content/ipc/uploads/projects/EN010012/EN010012-011164-SZC-Decision-Letter.pdf |format=PDF |location=London |publisher=Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy |access-date=27 July 2022 |id=EN010012}}</ref>

On 8 August 2022, Together Against Sizewell C (TASC), supported by [[Friends of the Earth (EWNI)|Friends of the Earth]], announced its intention to contest the development consent order, based primarily on the failure to first secure a water supply. In its earlier rejection of the scheme, the [[Planning Inspectorate]] had stated that "unless the outstanding water supply strategy can be resolved and sufficient information provided to enable the secretary of state to carry out his obligations under the Habitats Regulations, the case for an order granting development consent for the application is not made out".<ref name=guardian-20220808>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2022/aug/08/sizewell-c-nuclear-plant-approval-faces-legal-challenge |title=Sizewell C nuclear plant approval faces legal challenge |last=Laville |first=Sandra |newspaper=The Guardian |date=8 August 2022 |access-date=8 August 2022 |archive-date=8 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220808060127/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2022/aug/08/sizewell-c-nuclear-plant-approval-faces-legal-challenge |url-status=live}}</ref> In a ruling on 20 December 2023 the case was dismissed; "the Secretary of State was entitled in this case to regard the project as the power station, and that the provision of a permanent water supply was not part of that project but formed a different and separate project."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lindblom |first=Keith |date=20 December 2023 |title=Together Against Sizewell C Ltd, R (On the Application Of) v Secretary of State for Energy Security And Net Zero & Another |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/judgments/together-against-sizewell-c-limited-v-secretary-of-state-for-energy-security-and-net-zero-and-another/}}</ref> The TASC appeal to this ruling was dismissed on 13 May 2024 "because the application does not raise an arguable point of law".<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 May 2024 |title=Supreme Court refuses permission to hear the legal challenge to the Sizewell C development consent order |url=https://www.herbertsmithfreehills.com/notes/energy-and-infra-consenting/2024-05/supreme-court-refuses-permission-to-hear-the-legal-challenge-to-the-sizewell-c-development-consent-order}}</ref>

=== Concerns regarding coastal erosion ===
There are also concerns about coastal erosion near Sizewell, particularly following accelerated erosion at nearby [[Thorpeness]] since December 2024. [[David King (chemist)]], former chief scientific adviser to the UK government, highlighted that erosion in this area will amplify the impacts of rising sea levels.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news |last=Mooney |first=Attracta |last2=Millard |first2=Rachel |date=24 Feb 2026 |title=Rapid UK coastal erosion throws spotlight on £40bn nuclear plantC |url=https://www.ft.com/content/7f093296-41cd-498c-ba81-f3707204eca9 |url-access=subscription |access-date=2026-03-01 |work=FT}}</ref> Local residents accused the Sizewell developers of dredging 210,000 tonnes of gravel from the beach at Thorpeness to protect the plant; however this was refuted by a Sizewell C spokesperson.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-12-24 |title=Developers of Sizewell C say nuclear power station will not affect eroding coastline |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/25723021.sizewell-developer-responds-thorpeness-gravel-calls/ |access-date=2026-03-01 |website=East Anglian Daily Times |language=en}}</ref> Protecting the plant from the sea is a key concern. There are plans to construct {{Convert|14|m|abbr=on}} high defences using boulders.<ref name=":4" />

===Preference for other energy sources===
{{see also|Anti-nuclear movement#Nuclear-free alternatives}}
Researchers such as Professor Barrett et al at UCL claim, based on detailed cost studies, that a judicious mix of renewable energy, storage, hydrogen, and [[fossil fuel]] offers the same constant availability of power as Sizewell C, at lower cost.<ref>{{cite web |title=Baseload nuclear power not needed in an all-renewable future |url=https://claverton-energy.com/baseload-power-generators-such-as-nuclear-power-plant-are-not-needed-in-an-all-renewable-future-and-their-use-would-simply-increase-costs.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220721100851/https://claverton-energy.com/baseload-power-generators-such-as-nuclear-power-plant-are-not-needed-in-an-all-renewable-future-and-their-use-would-simply-increase-costs.html |archive-date=21 July 2022 |publisher=Claverton Group |quote=This reliability means that we can design systems at reasonable cost which use negligible amounts of fossil fuels for heat and electricity supply. Low-cost peaking fossil plant would be used in exceptional conditions. |access-date=22 July 2022}}</ref>

===Economic impacts on the local area===
Aldeburgh Town Council expressed concern about workers being attracted to jobs at the Sizewell C site. "Aldeburgh is a town with an economy firmly rooted in Tourism. ... Businesses simply cannot match the offers being made by SZC and have already lost staff to higher paid opportunities – this was also experienced during the construction of Sizewell B."<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 July 2024 |title=Sizewell C Main Development Site Forum |url=https://www.sizewellc.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/240716-Main-Development-Site-Forum-Presentation-Pack.pdf |page=62}}</ref>

==Archaeology==
In January 2025 it was reported that a [[hoard]] of coins from the 11th century had been found at the site. Oxford Cotswold Archaeology had discovered a cloth and lead package containing 321 silver coins, in mint condition, and believed the bundle could have been the savings of a local figure, fearing regime changes following the accession of [[Edward the Confessor]] in 1042. The coins date between 1036 and 1044, during the reigns of the Saxon kings [[Harold I]], [[Harthacnut]] and [[Edward the Confessor]]. The discovery was featured in a January 2025 episode of ''[[Digging for Britain]]'' (series 12, episode 1).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Digging for Britain. Series 12:1. Saxon Gold and Buried Coins |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m0026rh6/digging-for-britain-series-12-1-saxon-gold-and-buried-coins |access-date=2025-01-09 |website=BBC iPlayer |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c9wl9re5j1qo |title=Hoard of 11th Century coins found at Suffolk Sizewell C site |date=7 January 2025 |website=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/24837103.exquisite-hoard-silver-coins-unearthed-sizewell-c-site/ |title=Silver coin hoard nicknamed 'the pasty' is discovered at Sizewell C site |date=7 January 2025 |website=East Anglian Daily Times}}</ref>

In January 2026, archaeologists announced the uncovering of an Anglo-Saxon burial ground during preparatory excavations. The site, dating from the 6th to 7th centuries, includes at least 11 burial mounds (barrows) with both inhumation and [[cremation]] burials, many accompanied by weapons, jewellery and vessels, indicating varied funerary practices. Among the most remarkable finds is a high-status burial containing two individuals interred with a fully harnessed horse, weapons and personal items, interpreted as reflecting élite social status.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-12 |title=Princely burial with horse unearthed at Sizewell C excavation |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/c338dm8x0nmo |access-date=2026-01-17 |website=www.bbc.com |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-01-14 |title=Workers Discovered 1,400-Year-Old Royal Remains on the Grounds of a Nuclear Power Station |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/science/archaeology/a69989997/england-power-station-bodies/ |access-date=2026-01-17 |website=Popular Mechanics |language=en-US}}</ref>

In April 2026, archaeological investigations conducted ahead of construction at the Sizewell C site have revealed evidence of a Roman industrial landscape, including a well-preserved pottery kiln and features associated with salt production. The remains form part of a broader, multi-period archaeological sequence uncovered across the area, demonstrating long-term occupation and economic activity along the Suffolk coast. The industrial features suggest organised production linked to coastal resources, with salt-making and ceramic production likely forming part of a wider regional economy during the Roman period.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-04-15 |title=Corn dryers, kilns and craftsmanship: uncovering Roman industry on the Suffolk coast |url=https://oxfordcotswoldarchaeology.org.uk/news/szc-roman-industry/ |access-date=2026-04-16 |website=Oxford Cotswold Archaeology |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Milligan |first=Mark |date=2026-04-15 |title=Roman industrial hub discovered beneath Sizewell C construction site |url=https://www.heritagedaily.com/2026/04/roman-industrial-hub-discovered-beneath-sizewell-c-construction-site/157786 |access-date=2026-04-16 |website=HeritageDaily - Archaeology News |language=en-US}}</ref>

